                    <msContents>
                        <summary>A copy of a part of the Arabian Nights, often differently arranged
                            and numbered from any of the printed editions. Previous French owner
                            supplied several of the missing leaves.</summary>
                        <msItem xml:id="manuscript_14406_item_1">
                            <locus from="7a" to="264b">7a-264b</locus>
                            <title xml:lang="ar-Latn-x-lc" key="work_700">ʾAlf layla
                                wa-layla</title>
                            <title xml:lang="ar" type="alt">الف ليلة وليلة</title>
                            <title xml:lang="en" type="alt">Arabian nights</title>
                            <note><p>The numbering of the stories was added later, but it shows that
                                    this volume contained, when complete, 263 leaves comprising the
                                    sections (جزء) V-XII of the Arabian Nights. Before it reached
                                    the French owner's hands the fifth section had disappeared and
                                    the book then consisted of sections VI-XII with foliation 24-263
                                    (see old Eastern Arabic numerals in pen). A previous French
                                    owner supplied the missing leaves of Section V (folios
                                    7-13).</p>
                                <p>From the style (often half colloquial) used in the book, Mingana
                                    deduces that the recension is more Egyptian than Syrian or
                                    Mesopotamian, and there are even some words used in it which
                                    would hardly be understood in Syria or Iraq.</p>
                                <p>Marginal notes in pencil and in pen in French throughout.</p>
                                <p>The division to sections is purely arbitrary and mark no natural
                                    pauses.</p>
                                <p><list>
                                        <head>Contents:</head>
                                        <item>Folios 7a-29b: Contains the story of Khailakhān's
                                            adventures by sea and land related to a king of Persia
                                            whose name is given <quote>بدرجروان
                                            الريان</quote>;</item>
                                        <item>folios 30a-47b: The King of Persia and the two aged
                                            shaikhs who tell him stories. This ends with the story
                                            of King Iftikhāndār and his children and the marriage of
                                            Sitt al-Aqmār;</item>
                                        <item>folios 48a-264b: The long tale of ʿUmar an-Nuʿmān,
                                            King of Baghdad and Khurāsān, and his children and
                                            grandchildren. The story breaks off abruptly on folio
                                            264b, where it closes with a battle in which King
                                            Rūmazān of Constantinople and the Princess Nuzhat
                                            al-Zamān from Baghdad fight against each other.</item>
                                    </list></p>
                                <p>Folios 1-6: smaller leaves in French by previous French owner
                                    include a list of contents and portions of translations.</p>
                                <p>At the end of Section VIII on <locus from="127b">folio 127b</locus>, there is a colophon by the
                                    transcriber Nasīm bin Yūḥannā ibn Abu <quote>المساء</quote>, who
                                    states that he copied it from the most illustrious of maters,
                                    the Muʿallim Maṣari (possibly meant to be Miṣri or Maṣri) for
                                    the purpose of informing him concerning the events of ancient
                                    times. No date is given.</p>
                            </note>
                            <colophon></colophon>
